e|date=April 2010}}\n\nGauntlet was believed to have been killed<ref>''Wolverine'' vol. 2 #100</ref> after Wolverine used [[Deadbolt (comics)|Deadbolt's]] severed head to lure Gauntlet towards him and then savagely attacked him, though he later proved to have survived.{{Issue|date=April 2010}}\n\nFollowing the final defeat and disband of the Dark Riders, Gauntlet became a mercenary. [[Blaquesmith]] secretly contracted Gauntlet to hunt down Apocalypse when Apocalypse was merged with [[Cyclops (comics)|Cyclops]].{{Issue|date=April 2010}}\n\n==In other media==\n===Television===\nGauntlet made an appearance in the animated [[television]] show ''[[X-Men Evolution]]'' in the fourth season episode ''Target X''.  He is one of [[Hydra (comics)|HYDRA]]'s premiere agents, and is a master of hand-to-hand and armed combat. \n\nGauntlet appears to have been either genetically altered or possessed a natural mutation that makes him stronger, tougher, and with keener senses than the average human being. Like other agents of HYDRA, he has access to a wide array of tools and equipment that make him a formidable opponent and a dangerous tracker.\n\nUnfortunately for Gauntlet, he was aboard the [[hovercraft]] with the Supreme HYDRA which [[X-23]] destroyed. He was taken prisoner by [[S.H.I.E.L.D.|S.H.I.E.L.D. soldiers]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wolverine}}\n\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1991]]\n[[Category:Fictional assassins]]\n[[Category:Fictional mercenaries]]\n[[Category:Inhumans]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics supervillains]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Chris Claremont]]"}]}}}}